One of the key issues is that infinitesimals violate the concept of Archimedean property, which states that for any two positive real numbers, there is always another positive real number that lies between them. In other words, no matter how small a positive real number is, you can always find a smaller one. Infinitesimals, on the other hand, are smaller than any positive real number but are not considered to be zero. This violates the Archimedean property and leads to logical inconsistencies.
Another problem arises when we try to define basic arithmetic operations, such as addition and multiplication, involving infinitesimals. These operations can produce contradictory or nonsensical results. For example, if we have two infinitesimals, adding them together might give different results depending on how we approach the calculation. This lack of consistency undermines the reliability of using infinitesimals in mathematical reasoning.

